WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.080
Hello everyone.

00:00:08.080 --> 00:00:14.380
It's Wednesday night and I just sat down at my mom's bar, Sneakers.

00:00:14.380 --> 00:00:19.680
I can hear the band doing their soundcheck and I take a bite of my buffalo chicken and

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:24.520
I look across the bar and see my mom sit down next to a regular.

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:29.280
She strikes up a conversation with them and introduces them to my neighbor sitting a few

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:31.520
seats down.

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:38.560
I've witnessed this so many times at Sneakers that it's become commonplace to me.

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:44.919
But lately, probably the last year or so, I've thought a lot about the community building

00:00:44.919 --> 00:00:50.959
that she's done so naturally the past 38 years.

00:00:50.959 --> 00:00:56.880
And when I say growing up in a restaurant, I really mean that.

00:00:56.880 --> 00:01:01.240
This is my baby picture on the bar there at Sneakers.

00:01:01.240 --> 00:01:10.199
But jumping ahead, I'd say just about 30 years from there, I am now our manager of our professional

00:01:10.199 --> 00:01:13.639
community at RStudio.

00:01:13.639 --> 00:01:20.440
In my role, I get to work with a lot of you all, either in the room or watching virtually,

00:01:20.440 --> 00:01:27.639
and help connect customers to be able to share use cases and best practices and teach

00:01:27.639 --> 00:01:31.720
lessons learned with one another.

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:39.120
In doing so, I've learned that a lot of what makes us really good at our job is not what's

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:46.199
apparent in our resume or through our prior job experience or through the degree that

00:01:46.199 --> 00:01:48.760
we have.

00:01:48.760 --> 00:01:55.839
So when I think about my role in organizing and building community at RStudio, I realize

00:01:55.839 --> 00:01:57.839
I've been running my own bar.

00:01:57.839 --> 00:02:05.639
There are four, well, there's so many things that you can learn from restaurant experience

00:02:05.639 --> 00:02:12.279
itself, but there are four key takeaways that I want to share with you all today that you

00:02:12.279 --> 00:02:20.240
can take in building communities of your own or growing communities of your own.

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:28.360
So the first one, find your Taco Tuesday or be consistent.

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:35.000
At Sneakers and at a lot of restaurants, I'm sure we know, there are certain days that

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:42.399
are often associated with certain foods or certain days that are associated with certain

00:02:42.399 --> 00:02:44.500
events.

00:02:44.500 --> 00:02:55.720
At Sneakers, this could be having tacos on Tuesday or live music on Wednesday and Saturday.

00:02:55.720 --> 00:03:02.080
And people don't come to every single event, but when they have a free night or when they're

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:08.039
looking for something to do with friends, they know exactly where they can go.

00:03:08.039 --> 00:03:14.000
And so I try to do this with our events at RStudio as well.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:22.360
So every Tuesday at 12 Eastern time, I host the RStudio Enterprise Community Meetup.

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:27.600
And this is a meetup event for people to just share what they're doing.

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:35.600
So they may share a new use case or a best practice learned and present for 30 minutes

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:39.179
and take questions from the community.

00:03:39.179 --> 00:03:43.320
And so these happen every Tuesday at 12 Eastern time.

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:50.679
And it may be people gathering around an industry group like using R in healthcare or more broadly

00:03:50.679 --> 00:03:55.199
using Shiny in production.

00:03:55.199 --> 00:04:02.679
Also every Thursday at 12 Eastern time, I host our Data Science Hangout, which I see

00:04:02.679 --> 00:04:06.119
a few people here who have been to those as well.

00:04:06.119 --> 00:04:09.000
This is a little bit less formal.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:15.039
Not that the other is formal at all either, but there's no presentation at these.

00:04:15.039 --> 00:04:19.820
It's just a different data science leader from the community who joins me to answer

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:22.200
questions from the community.

00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:28.839
So all the questions are audience-led from you all and could be questions like, how do

00:04:28.839 --> 00:04:31.519
I talk to executives?

00:04:31.519 --> 00:04:35.519
Or how are you thinking about hiring right now?

00:04:35.519 --> 00:04:40.839
Should I have a centralized or decentralized data science team?

00:04:40.839 --> 00:04:44.279
These are every Thursday at 12 Eastern time.

00:04:44.279 --> 00:04:49.239
I've included the link to the calendar for these if you ever want to add the individual

00:04:49.239 --> 00:04:55.440
events or just the whole series of events to your calendar.

00:04:55.440 --> 00:05:00.119
This one's best formatted for your phone, but if you're on your desktop, add an extra

00:05:00.119 --> 00:05:04.480
dash and type calendar, and it will look a lot nicer too.

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:09.380
But if you're also an organizer, I just wanted to include that the tool that I use here is

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:12.040
called Add Event.

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:13.040
I really like that.

00:05:13.040 --> 00:05:18.480
It makes it really easy to share events that people can just put on their calendar without

00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:20.600
having to give me any information.

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:23.600
So find your Taco Tuesday.

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:27.239
Secondly, start conversations across the bar.

00:05:27.239 --> 00:05:35.040
So as I opened up with that scene, imagine the regular sitting alone at the bar.

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:40.600
My mom might walk over to them and strike up a conversation with them and the couple

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:43.799
sitting a few seats down.

00:05:43.799 --> 00:05:50.040
It might be about the band that's playing next week that she knows that they both like,

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:54.399
or it could be about a special that's on the menu that somebody else ordered across the

00:05:54.399 --> 00:05:56.000
bar too.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.839
The topic itself doesn't really matter as much.

00:06:00.839 --> 00:06:05.279
It's just that she's giving permission for that interaction to happen and kicking off

00:06:05.279 --> 00:06:08.040
the conversation.

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:12.440
She might start the conversation and then have to go walk away and run to the kitchen

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:16.720
and help with something or make a drink behind the bar.

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:21.200
But that person sitting alone at the bar might stay a little bit longer because they now

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:23.359
know somebody.

00:06:23.359 --> 00:06:31.640
Or they might come back more regularly because they feel a part of the sneakers community.

00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:37.000
I think one of the sneakers regulars said it best, and this is a newspaper article from

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:39.160
a few years ago.

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:42.239
But Deb is someone who I've known for many years now.

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:45.600
She's filmed employee weddings.

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:50.079
She actually made a video for my high school volleyball team.

00:06:50.079 --> 00:06:54.920
But Deb said, it's the kind of place where you can go in alone, have some food and a

00:06:54.920 --> 00:07:00.480
glass of wine, and pretty soon you are a part of the conversation.

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:07.760
I want people to feel this way at our studio community events as well, minus the food and

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:11.239
wine except for this week.

00:07:11.239 --> 00:07:19.640
But as community organizers, we have a responsibility to bring people together based on shared interests.

00:07:19.640 --> 00:07:23.880
And I think it's important here that these interests aren't something that we ourselves

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:27.839
have to be experts on.

00:07:27.839 --> 00:07:34.359
But we can go a step further here to help kick off conversations with people at events

00:07:34.359 --> 00:07:36.519
as well.

00:07:36.519 --> 00:07:42.679
I think one of my favorite examples of this comes from the Data Science Hangout, which

00:07:42.679 --> 00:07:47.239
happens every Thursday at 12 Eastern time.

00:07:47.239 --> 00:07:54.679
But this particular week featured Kristy Angel, a data science manager from Stitch Fix.

00:07:54.679 --> 00:08:01.260
And leading up to that session, a few people had reached out to me on LinkedIn or maybe

00:08:01.260 --> 00:08:10.019
at meetups as well and mentioned that they're really having a hard time finding a new job.

00:08:10.019 --> 00:08:15.579
And they were hitting roadblocks with recruiters and not getting through to a hiring manager

00:08:15.579 --> 00:08:19.179
because they didn't have a certain degree.

00:08:19.179 --> 00:08:24.459
So I had the privilege of knowing this as the organizer of the group and getting to

00:08:24.459 --> 00:08:26.859
talk with all these people.

00:08:26.859 --> 00:08:32.820
So I was able to ask this to Kristy for them anonymously, just to get her insights and

00:08:32.820 --> 00:08:36.380
hear her experience.

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:45.179
And I started to see in the chat that everybody started commenting with their own degrees

00:08:45.179 --> 00:08:51.099
and their own non-data science degrees in a room full of data scientists, or a Zoom

00:08:51.099 --> 00:08:54.840
room full of data scientists.

00:08:54.840 --> 00:09:02.559
And it was just one of those moments that you just remember, just seeing people all

00:09:02.559 --> 00:09:09.320
supporting each other and cheering each other on for their non-data science degrees and

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:14.640
supporting people who are running into this right now.

00:09:14.640 --> 00:09:18.479
So start those conversations across the bar.

00:09:18.479 --> 00:09:23.159
Third, touch every table.

00:09:23.159 --> 00:09:29.200
So at Sneakers, it's pretty much a guarantee if you go in for dinner, my mom will come

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:33.320
by your table and thank you for coming in.

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:34.919
If it's her night to work, of course.

00:09:34.919 --> 00:09:40.559
If it's her business partner Annie's night to work, she'll be the one to come by.

00:09:40.559 --> 00:09:47.919
And it doesn't matter if you are regular or this is your first time coming into Sneakers.

00:09:47.919 --> 00:09:54.760
She'll stop by and say thank you for coming in and ask where you're from, how you're enjoying

00:09:54.760 --> 00:10:00.479
your meal, or maybe reminiscing with customers who have become like family.

00:10:00.479 --> 00:10:07.280
I actually had no idea this was a term until preparing for this talk, but table touching

00:10:07.280 --> 00:10:10.679
is a real thing in the restaurant industry.

00:10:10.679 --> 00:10:17.479
And there's a lot of articles about how touching every table can help create a guest for life.

00:10:18.479 --> 00:10:28.000
In the virtual world, I want to be able to stop by and meet you at your table as well.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:36.239
The way that I like to do this is when people join a meetup or a data science hangout, is

00:10:36.239 --> 00:10:45.039
to write down the names of people who mentioned they're joining for the very first time, or

00:10:45.039 --> 00:10:48.799
maybe it's just a name that I haven't seen joined before.

00:10:48.799 --> 00:10:55.840
But also write down a few names of people who have been coming back regularly, or faces

00:10:55.840 --> 00:11:00.359
that I've been seeing on Zoom.

00:11:00.359 --> 00:11:04.440
This is not possible, I know, with hundreds of people, but I don't think that's a reason

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:06.679
to not do it at all.

00:11:06.679 --> 00:11:14.919
So I might say to myself, today I'm going to write down the names of five regulars.

00:11:14.919 --> 00:11:17.960
And five new people.

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:21.159
And I'll reach out to them on LinkedIn just to say thank you.

00:11:21.159 --> 00:11:27.479
Thank you for joining, or thank you for the comment that you put into the chat.

00:11:27.479 --> 00:11:33.479
So it might be just a few people that week, but hopefully, as we go, I get to reach out

00:11:33.479 --> 00:11:35.479
to everybody.

00:11:35.479 --> 00:11:39.520
So touch every table.

00:11:39.520 --> 00:11:47.039
And the last takeaway I want to leave you with, which also expands on the last one.

00:11:47.039 --> 00:11:52.719
Sometimes when you're going by and visiting with a table, you get a chance to learn more

00:11:52.719 --> 00:11:58.840
about someone's experience and how you can make that a little bit better.

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:06.799
But not only in what they're telling you, but in observing the unsaid.

00:12:06.799 --> 00:12:11.200
So I think I've given you enough restaurant examples right now that I can put you in the

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:14.080
role of owner.

00:12:14.080 --> 00:12:23.640
So let's say over here we have our table of four who are waiting for trivia night to start.

00:12:23.640 --> 00:12:28.200
They all ordered a round of drinks, three of them are finishing up, and you walk by

00:12:28.200 --> 00:12:31.640
their table to check in on them.

00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:39.080
You notice, though, that one of the drinks is pushed over to the side.

00:12:39.080 --> 00:12:42.359
Now you ask them how their night's going, they say everything's great.

00:12:42.359 --> 00:12:48.039
But you can tell they probably didn't enjoy their drink as much as they would have liked

00:12:48.039 --> 00:12:52.280
to by the way that it's pushed over to the side.

00:12:52.280 --> 00:12:56.840
So you look at that and take it as an opportunity to ask them if there's something else that

00:12:56.840 --> 00:13:04.000
you could get them and insist that you want them to have something that they'd enjoy.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:08.640
This doesn't have to just be about untouched food or drinks.

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:13.840
It could also be about stopping by a table and noticing that it's somebody's birthday

00:13:13.840 --> 00:13:18.679
and noticing that before they actually told you.

00:13:18.679 --> 00:13:22.359
Just noticing the little things.

00:13:22.359 --> 00:13:28.400
This dining experience looks a little bit different in a virtual world.

00:13:28.400 --> 00:13:30.960
So let me just take you on a journey here.

00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:37.479
So we'll look at my, this little stick figure here, and we can imagine it as anyone, but

00:13:37.479 --> 00:13:39.700
we'll call him Bob.

00:13:39.700 --> 00:13:46.000
So Bob joins a meetup event for the first time and listens in.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:50.640
Maybe Bob was on the list of one of the five people that I wrote down as a new person or

00:13:50.640 --> 00:13:52.760
maybe he wasn't.

00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:58.799
He comes back again and joins in listen-only mode again.

00:13:58.799 --> 00:14:05.239
A week later, he comments in the chat, and then I notice Bob unmutes briefly, it pops

00:14:05.239 --> 00:14:11.559
up to the top of my Zoom, but doesn't end up speaking.

00:14:11.559 --> 00:14:18.919
So I'm not going to say to Bob on LinkedIn, hey, you joined three times and you never

00:14:18.919 --> 00:14:23.280
talk, what can I do to make you feel more comfortable?

00:14:23.280 --> 00:14:28.200
But I might say something like, hey, Bob, thanks so much for joining today.

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:33.159
I loved your comment about learning R as a SaaS user.

00:14:33.159 --> 00:14:37.020
I think that perspective was incredibly helpful.

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:42.359
If you ever have any suggestions or things that we could be doing to make this event

00:14:42.359 --> 00:14:46.840
more useful, please let me know.

00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:51.400
And Bob might say, thanks for joining, I had a great time.

00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:58.840
I wanted to ask a question, but I wasn't sure if it was the right format.

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:04.799
And so I've had the opportunity now to learn something more about Bob's experience by thanking

00:15:04.799 --> 00:15:14.919
him for coming and by just noticing that there was something there in the unsaid.

00:15:14.919 --> 00:15:23.080
And so what Bob does for me here is I have that opportunity to say, did you, oh, gosh,

00:15:23.080 --> 00:15:26.799
this is, there we go.

00:15:26.799 --> 00:15:31.559
Did you know that you can ask questions anonymously as well?

00:15:31.559 --> 00:15:38.400
And so I can let him know this is a place for any question to be asked, but there's

00:15:38.400 --> 00:15:40.059
something more there.

00:15:40.059 --> 00:15:46.280
And he points out to me that I didn't make it clear maybe in the beginning of the presentation

00:15:46.280 --> 00:15:50.140
that people could ask questions anonymously.

00:15:50.140 --> 00:15:54.979
And if I said that once, maybe that's not enough.

00:15:54.979 --> 00:15:59.140
Because if somebody joined a few minutes later, they would have missed that.

00:15:59.140 --> 00:16:05.460
So it lets me know that that's something I should put in the chat as well.

00:16:05.460 --> 00:16:12.260
So months later, maybe he keeps coming back and keeps joining, and eventually presents

00:16:12.260 --> 00:16:14.979
at the meetup as well.

00:16:14.979 --> 00:16:20.940
I think this is one of my favorite things about community building, is seeing somebody

00:16:20.940 --> 00:16:28.460
come for the very first time, and then starting to get to know people, and you see them, like,

00:16:28.460 --> 00:16:32.979
being friends on Twitter or commenting on each other's LinkedIn posts.

00:16:32.979 --> 00:16:41.940
And then eventually that person being the one presenting at the event too.

00:16:41.940 --> 00:16:51.219
So today I've given you four key takeaways that I've learned from growing up at Sneakers.

00:16:51.219 --> 00:16:57.020
But there are so many more tips out there from amazing community builders and community

00:16:57.020 --> 00:17:00.460
organizers like you all.

00:17:00.460 --> 00:17:05.819
I know there are so many here in the audience today, at the conference, and watching virtually

00:17:05.819 --> 00:17:07.859
as well.

00:17:07.859 --> 00:17:13.219
So I wanted to take this opportunity to share this resource as well.

00:17:13.219 --> 00:17:15.060
A few months ago, I guess it's not that new now.

00:17:15.060 --> 00:17:25.380
A few months ago, I helped build a site, rstudio.com champion, and it was designed to help people

00:17:25.380 --> 00:17:29.979
advocate for data science at their own organizations.

00:17:29.979 --> 00:17:33.619
And when they're facing roadblocks, to have a place to go.

00:17:33.619 --> 00:17:37.699
But also included a section on community building.

00:17:37.699 --> 00:17:45.619
And this includes a lot of knowledge and resources from amazing community builders out there,

00:17:45.619 --> 00:17:50.219
and people that I've met at other events.

00:17:50.219 --> 00:17:57.180
There's also a feedback form on the very bottom of this site, if you scroll to it, where you

00:17:57.180 --> 00:18:00.979
can share your own tips and tricks.

00:18:00.979 --> 00:18:08.500
Or ask to see something else that's maybe not there yet.

00:18:08.500 --> 00:18:14.660
I just want to say thank you so much to all of you for being here today, and it's amazing

00:18:14.660 --> 00:18:18.819
to see you all at the conference, too.

00:18:18.819 --> 00:18:25.300
I want to say a big thank you to my mom, Rhonda Dempsey, who I learned so much from and continue

00:18:25.300 --> 00:18:28.219
to learn so much from.

00:18:28.219 --> 00:18:35.640
Also a huge congrats to her and her business partner, Annie, who are celebrating 38 years

00:18:35.640 --> 00:18:47.339
in business at Sneakers Cafe this week.

00:18:47.339 --> 00:18:51.540
And also feel like in case my mom and dad were watching, to say happy anniversary to

00:18:51.540 --> 00:18:55.660
them, too, because today is their actual anniversary.

00:18:55.660 --> 00:19:03.219
But just like Sneakers would not be the same without their community, R and RStudio, and

00:19:03.219 --> 00:19:08.739
soon to be Posit, would definitely not be the same without all of you.

00:19:08.739 --> 00:19:10.979
Thank you so much, again, for being here.

00:19:10.979 --> 00:19:15.660
If you have any questions, I'd love to hear them, but I'd also put my LinkedIn and Twitter

00:19:15.660 --> 00:19:20.380
up on the screen as well, because I would love to connect there.

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:22.780
LinkedIn is probably the preference.

00:19:22.780 --> 00:19:27.939
I'll also take questions on the Discord channel communities of practice, too.

00:19:27.939 --> 00:19:28.939
Thank you, everybody.

00:19:28.939 --> 00:19:29.939
Thank you.

00:19:29.939 --> 00:19:29.939


